The term "den of iniquity" is used to depict a place of immoral behavior, usually of a sexual type. The origin of the term can be traced back to the Old Testament of the Bible. It was not until recent times that this turn of phrase has come into our everyday language usage.

In both  Mark and Matthew, Jesus condemns those who have been using the sacred temple as a marketplace, proclaiming that they have "made it a den of thieves." The word "iniquity" appears numerous times in the Bible with the meaning of "injustice" or "sin." To this day, writers use the word "den" to mean a place where iniquitous activities are carried out.

Despite all this, the exact idiom "den of iniquity" does not appear in written English until the 20th century. The song "In Our Little Den of Iniquity" from the 1950s musical "Pal Joey" is an early example. It refers to a secret hideaway for romantic rendezvous. Used more solemnly, the expression "den of iniquity" implies a certain discernment that a morally upright person would consider intolerable.